speechtext:
Mrs. Robichaud filed a complaint of discrimination against the Department of National Defence in January, 1980. On December 15, 1980, following conciliation, the Canadian Human Rights Commission requested the appointment of a Human Rights Tribunal.
In addition to supporting the complaint through investigation and attempting conciliation, the commission:
Paid for outside counsel to act both on its behalf and on behalf of Mrs. Robichaud during the proceedings before the tribunal. All expenses involved with the Tribunal proceedings were borne by the commission;
Did not appeal the tribunal decision as the general counsel advised the commission there was little chance of success;
Offered to argue the case on behalf of Mrs. Robichaud when the case proceeded to review tribunal, but the offer was declined. Commission counsel appeared at the review tribunal and made submissions supporting Mrs. Robichaud and submitted legal argument on all points of law;
Appeared separately through counsel at Federal Court and argued in favour of a ruling upholding the review tribunal's decision on liability;
Obtained leave to appeal to the Supreme Court of Canada on the question of the liability of DND for the acts of the supervisor.
In October 1985, Mrs. Robichaud and DND arrived at a confidential settlement of her complaint. The CHRC was not a party to this settlement and was not advised of its terms until the summer of 1988. The commission's counsel was present throughout the hearings of the review tribunal which took place during late 1988 and 1989.
